      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-42092" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://www.blossomingtwigswordpress.com" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Kristin Brown</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2014/12/december-5/#comment-42092"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2014-12-08T15:38:36-05:00">Monday, December 8, 2014 at 3:38 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I checked out Rachel Roddy, albeit briefly, and her site looks interesting.  I&#39;m always one for reading about someone&#39;s experience in another country. </p>
<p>I finished Delancey in just a few days,  It&#39;s what got me through the stress of a moving truck arriving at our house with way too much stuff.  I was kind of jonesing for something like it (I read your first book quite a few years ago), but alas I haven&#39;t found anything in a similar vain.  I found myself waiting for another blog post, so I was happy to read this one.  </p>
<p>During the interim I read some past posts and came upon one where you talked about the smell of Colorado, in it you linked to a camp.  I know that smell you were talking about, as I live in Colorado and I attended Geneva Glen.  I had forgotten.  I spent at least two summers up there, as did my sister and I think my brother too.  I remember the archery, the songs around the campfire, the general store where I could buy my own candy, and the big pool where we made a huge tidal wave by so many people going round and round in a circle.  It was nice to be reminded.</p>
<p>Since this is suppose to be a comment and not an article, I&#39;ll start to take my leave, but&#8230;<br />one of my favorite books still, after having read it at least 3 times in the last 5 years, in answer to something to read, is Mountains Beyond Mountains:  The Quest of Dr. Paul Farmer, a Man Would Cure the World by Tracy Kidder.  I literally pick up a used copy every time I see one, so that I can give the book away to someone new.  It&#39;s an incredibly inspiring book.</p>
<p>I have a child on my lap wanting me to read his favorite book about trucks, so ado.</p>
<p>Feel better. </p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-42093" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://curlygirlpress.wordpress.com/" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">curlygirlpress</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2014/12/december-5/#comment-42093"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2014-12-08T18:45:05-05:00">Monday, December 8, 2014 at 6:45 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>When my little was in his first winter season at daycare we were sick, I swear non-stop, for a couple of months &#8211; all three of us together and in stages.  May you reach the end of this soon!  If you don&#39;t mind YA fiction, the Cinder/Scarlet/Cress trio is fast and clever (with that dose of teen angst they all have = )</p>
    </div>

